isruption, companies knew that robots were cheaper, more productive, and an=
d came with less baggage than human workers. During previous waves of autom=
ation (or ahead of potential waves of automation), the fear has been that r=
obots would replace humans and leave millions of workers out of a job, or a=
t the very least, worse off. That fear seems to be less pervasive today bec=
ause, in the face of labor shortages, clogged supply chains, and on-shoring=
 trends, we simply need more resources and productivity.</p><p style=3D"col=
