trong><span>&#8221; that not only does American </span><em>need </em><span>=
more robots, but that robots are actually </span><em>good </em><span>for th=
e U.S. worker. Smith addresses the notion that robots will displace the Ame=
rican worker noting that basically everyone who wants a job, has a job &#82=
12; and that low-skill wages (the jobs most likely to be automated away) ha=
ve actually steadily increased with automation. He also tends to agree with=
 our argument above &#8212; if the U.S. is to reshore its industrial base f=
rom China, it needs to lean into its strength. Our strength, relatively spe=
aking, is not cheap and abundant labor, but rather capital and advanced tec=
hnology. If we&#8217;re going to compete with Chinese manufacturing, we nee=
d to lean into those strengths, which is to say: we need more advanced robo=
ts.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
